    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-04T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-04T13:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795B.5/8–150: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-04T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 4, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>60. Reurtel 98<note n="1" xml:id="d395fn1">Received on August 1 at 5:07 a. m.,
                            <ref target="#pg_511">p. 511</ref>.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> understands from <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                        >Dept</gloss> Defense that emergency auth given Gen MacArthur immed fol
                    outbreak hostilities permitting him, as operational expedient, fulfill, without
                    limitation, all <gloss target="#t_KMAG1">KMAG</gloss>’s requests for material on
                    behalf <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>. It further understood MacArthur
                    utilizing this auth to meet current requirements Korean forces.</p>
                <p>For your further info <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> informing <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> its opinion that <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> 8/2<note n="2" xml:id="d395fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1949v07p2#pg_969">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1949, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, Part 2, p. 969</ref>.</note> which
                    imposed limitation of 65,000 troops, now obsolete.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
